# Main Idea: Call by Value in C

In **C**, when we pass arguments to a function, they are passed **by value**.

This means:

> The function receives a **copy of the value**, not the original variable.

So if the function changes the value, **the original variable in the main program does not change**.

---

# Simple Example

```c
void change(int x)
{
    x = 10;
}
```

```c
int a = 5;
change(a);
```

After the function runs:

```id="1mqczs"
a = 5
```

Even though inside the function:

```id="l3py6t"
x = 10
```

Why?

Because **x is just a copy of a**.

